  <li>fire and public safety</li>\n  <li>social care</li>\n  <li>libraries</li>\n  <li>waste management</li>\n  <li>trading standards</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>District, borough and city councils</h2>\n<p>These cover a smaller area than county councils. They’re usually responsible for services like:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>rubbish collection</li>\n  <li>recycling</li>\n  <li>Council Tax collections</li>\n  <li>housing</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Unitary authorities</h2>\n<p>In some parts of the country, one tier of local government provides all the local services listed above.</p>\n\n<h2>Parish, community and town councils</h2>\n<p>These operate at a level below district and borough councils and in some cases, unitary authorities. They&rsquo;re elected and can help on a number of local issues, like:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>planning applications</li>\n  <li>running sports grounds</li>\n  <li>running community halls</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/understand-how-your-council-works/decision-making","slug":"decision-making","order":2,"title":"Decision making","body":"<p>The full council (a meeting of all council members) is responsible for all decisions. But in practice, most of the work is given to smaller groups of councillors or council officers (paid staff).</p>\n\n<p>Every council must publish:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>details of when key decisions will be taken</li>\n  <li>papers of meetings – at least 5 working days beforehand</li>\n  <li>minutes of meetings – showing the decisions that were made</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can view council meeting agendas, minutes and reports on <a href=\"/find-your-local-council\" title=\"Find your local council\">your council&rsquo;s website</a>.</p>\n\n<p>You can also attend most council meetings, although usually you won’t be able to speak at them.</p>\n\n<h2>Mayors</h2>\n<p>Many councils have a civic mayor or chairman of the council. They carry out ceremonial duties and chair meetings, but can&rsquo;t make decisions about council business.</p>\n\